VITAMIN D TOXICITY - USA: CANINE, PET FOOD RECALL
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 12 Nov 2018
Source: ABC Action News [edited]
https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/dog-food-recall-vitamin-d-toxicity


Two types of dry dog food have been recalled after 3 separate reports from pet owners indicated their pets were suffering from vitamin D toxicity as a result of eating the food. Natural Life Pet Products is voluntarily recalling Natural Life Chicken and Potato dry dog food in 8 states, and Nutrisca is voluntarily recalling its Chicken and Chickpea Dry Dog Food nationwide.

An investigation into the matter found that a formula error led to the products containing too much vitamin D, the recall page on the US Food and Drug Administration website stated. The specifics on which dry dog foods are being recalled are listed below:

- 17.5 lb [7.9 kg] Natural Life Chicken and Potato Dry Dog Food Bag (UPC: 0-12344-08175-1)
Bags affected have a "best by date" code of 4 Dec 2019 through 10 Aug 2020. The code can be found on the back or bottom of each bag. The affected dog food was distributed by the St Louis-based company to retail stores in Georgia, Florida, Alabama, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia, and California.
- 4 lb [1.8 kg] Nutrisca Chicken and Chickpea Dry Dog Food Bag (UPC: 8-84244-12495-7)
- 15 lb [6.8 kg] Nutrisca Chicken and Chickpea Dry Dog Food Bag (UPC: 8-84244-12795-8)
- 28 lb [12.7] Nutrisca Chicken and Chickpea Dry Dog Food Bag (UPC: 8-84244-12895-5)
Bags affected have a "best by date" code of 25 Feb 2020 through 13 Sep 2020. The dry dog food was distributed nationwide.

Too much vitamin D can negatively affect dogs. Clinical signs of vitamin D toxicity include vomiting, loss of appetite, increased thirst, increased urination, excessive drooling, and weight loss. It can also lead to renal dysfunction (problems with the kidneys).

If your dog has eaten any of these foods and is exhibiting the signs of vitamin D toxicity, you are urged to contact your veterinarian.

Consumers with more questions on either recall can contact Natural Life Pet Products at 1-888-279-9420, 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. CST, Monday through Friday. The company can also be reached by email at <consumerservices@nutrisca.com>.

[byline: Susan Gonzalez]

